<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="250" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1436,1596,1729]" pageId="11" pageNumber="250">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,260,1596,1621]" pageId="11" pageNumber="250">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[274,469,1598,1621]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rutaceae" genus="Hortia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="11" pageNumber="250" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="arriuensis">
<emphasis box="[274,469,1598,1621]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="250">Hortia arriuensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterized by its fragile shell and a well-developed anal notch. The protoconch I is covered by minute granules (
<figureCitation box="[501,567,1632,1657]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="12.[151,255,1946,1969]" captionTargetBox="[184,1402,719,1924]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[184,1402,711,1925]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 5. Fossil species of Hortia Lozouet, 1999. A – C. Hortia arriuensis Lozouet, 1999, MNHN. F. A 47751, Upper Oligocene, St-Etienne-d’Orthe, Landes, France. D – G. Hortia priabonica n. sp., Upper Eocene, Cagnotte, Landes, France [D – F. MNHN. F. A 47752, holotype. G. MNHN. F. A 47753, paratype]." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/251556/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="250">
Fig. 
<number box="[553,567,1632,1657]" pageId="11" pageNumber="250" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
B–C). 
<taxonomicName box="[641,834,1632,1657]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rutaceae" genus="Hortia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="11" pageNumber="250" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pseudotaranis" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[641,834,1632,1657]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="250">H. pseudotaranis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[840,900,1633,1656]" pageId="11" pageNumber="250" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[968,1142,1632,1657]" name="New Caledonia" pageId="11" pageNumber="250">New Caledonia</collectingCountry>
is remarkably similar to it in sculpture pattern. 
<taxonomicName box="[383,579,1670,1693]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rutaceae" genus="Hortia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="11" pageNumber="250" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="arriuensis">
<emphasis box="[383,579,1670,1693]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="250">Hortia arriuensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is common in the Upper bathyal deposits of the paleocanyon of Saubrigues (
<bibRefCitation author="Lozouet" box="[158,320,1705,1729]" pageId="11" pageNumber="250" refString="Lozouet, P. (2004) The European Tertiary Neritiliidae (Mollusca, Gastropoda, Neritopsina): indicators of tropical submarine cave environments and freshwater faunas. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 140, 447 - 467, 9 figs. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.2003.00099. x" type="journal article" year="2004">
Lozouet 
<number box="[259,320,1705,1729]" pageId="11" pageNumber="250" value="2004.0">2004</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
